events.description: Dick Whittington was a very little boy when his father and mother died; so little, indeed, that he never knew them, nor the place where he was born. He strolled about the country as ragged as a colt, till he met with a wagoner who was going to London, and who gave him leave to walk all the way by the side of his wagon without paying anything for his passage.

This pleased little Whittington very much, as he wanted to see London sadly, for he had heard that the streets were paved with gold, and he was willing to get a bushel of it; but how great was his disappointment, poor boy! when he saw the streets covered with dirt instead of gold, and found himself in a strange place, without a friend, without food, and without money.

Though the wagoner was so charitable as to let him walk up by the side of the wagon for nothing, he took care not to know him when he came to town, and the poor boy was, in a little time, so cold and hungry that he wished himself in a good kitchen and by a warm fire in the country.
In his distress he asked charity of several people, and one of them bid him Go to work for an idle rogue. That I will, said Whittington, with all my heart; I will work for you if you will let me.

The man, who thought this savored of wit and impertinence (though the poor lad intended only to show his readiness to work), gave him a blow with a stick which broke his head so that the blood ran down.

In this situation, and fainting for want of food, he laid himself down at the door of one Mr. Fitzwarren, a merchant, where the cook saw him, and, being an ill-natured hussy, she did not help him but instead told him to go away.
The merchant, however, took pity on Whittington and gave him some food and shelter, but the cook continued to be cruel to him and made his life miserable in the house.
Whittington was forced to clean the kitchen and do other menial tasks, but he did not complain and instead tried to make the best of the situation.
One day, Whittington found a cat in the kitchen and adopted it as his own, naming her Miss Puss. The cat became Whittington's constant companion and friend.
The merchant and his family were surprised by the cat's intelligence and cunning, but they did not know that she was about to become famous throughout the land.

One day, a factor from a ship arrived at the house with news of the cat's incredible exploits. The factor told them that Miss Puss had killed all the rats and mice on board the ship and had even saved the cargo from destruction.
The King and Queen were so impressed by the story that they ordered the captain and factor to bring the cat to their court, where she would be rewarded for her services.
When the captain and factor arrived at the house with the news, Mr. Fitzwarren was overjoyed and immediately went to get Whittington from his work in the kitchen.
Whittington was amazed by the news and could not believe that his cat had become famous throughout the land. He thanked God for His providential care of such a poor and miserable creature.
The captain and factor told Mr. Fitzwarren about the incredible exploits of Miss Puss, and he was so impressed that he decided to give Whittington all the treasure that the cat had earned.
